White wine quality by exploring physicochemical properties data by Raafat Saleh ===============

Introduction

The dataset is related to White Wine of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. For more details, consult: http://www.vinhoverde.pt/en/ or the reference [Cortez et al., 2009]. Due to privacy and logistic issues, only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (the output) variables are available (e.g.there is no data about grape types, wine brand, wine selling price, etc.). Also, we are not sure if all input variables are relevant. So it could be interesting to test feature selection methods.

  • Number of Instances (obs.): 4898.
  • Number of Attributes (variables): 11 + output attribute + serial No (x var.)

I notice 11 variables are numerics, on quantifying the chemical properties of the wine, except quality variable is integer. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). Ill convert quality as a factor variable to help me for exploration. Befor that, Ill remove the the x variable because it isnt needed in my analysis.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.800   6.300   6.800   6.855   7.300  14.200

Fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g/dm^3) most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily). The fixed acidity follows a normal distribution with mean 6.855 (the median 6.800 g/dm^3) and some outliers over 14 and under 4 (3.800). The 75% of the data is below 7.3 g/dm^3.

To make the plot more readable and remove some outliers in the right side of the plot, 99 percentile is used to limit the upper bound of the xlimit. The histogram now look more a normal distribution.
